1. Properly Designing RESTful APIs

a. Resource URIs:

(i) Use nouns, not verbs, for resource names.
Good: /users, /orders/123
Bad: /getUser, /createOrder

(ii) Use plural nouns for collections.
/users (all users), /users/1 (user with ID 1)

(iii) Hierarchical relationships in URIs.
/users/1/orders (orders for user 1)

b. HTTP Verbs (Methods)

GET: Retrieve data (safe, no side effects)
GET /users (get all users)
GET /users/1 (get user with ID 1)
POST: Create a new resource
POST /users (create a new user)
PUT: Update/replace a resource
PUT /users/1 (replace user 1)
PATCH: Partially update a resource
PATCH /users/1 (update some fields of user 1)
DELETE: Remove a resource
DELETE /users/1 (delete user 1)

Example Controller:

@RestController
@RequestMapping("/users")
public class UserController {
    @GetMapping public List<User> getAllUsers() { ... }
    @GetMapping("/{id}") public User getUser(@PathVariable Long id) { ... }
    @PostMapping public User createUser(@RequestBody User user) { ... }
    @PutMapping("/{id}") public User updateUser(@PathVariable Long id, @RequestBody User user) { ... }
    @DeleteMapping("/{id}") public void deleteUser(@PathVariable Long id) { ... }
}

2. Avoiding Anti-Patterns

(i) Don’t use GET for actions that modify data.
Bad: GET /users/delete/1
Good: DELETE /users/1

(ii) Don’t use verbs in URIs.
Bad: /getUser, /updateUser
Good: /users/1

(iii) Don’t expose internal database structure.
Avoid URIs like /users_table

(iv) Don’t use complex query parameters for actions.
Bad: GET /users?action=delete&id=1
Good: DELETE /users/1

(v) Don’t return 200 OK for errors.
Use proper status codes (404 for not found, 400 for bad request, etc.)

3. Structuring APIs to Conform to REST Standards & Richardson Maturity Model

a. Richardson Maturity Model Levels

Level 0: One endpoint, one method (not RESTful)
Level 1: Multiple endpoints for resources, but only one method (e.g., POST)
Level 2: Multiple endpoints, proper use of HTTP methods (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE)
Level 3: Hypermedia controls (HATEOAS) — include links in responses

Aim for at least Level 2 for most APIs.

b. RESTful API Structure

(i) Use standard HTTP status codes.
200 OK (success), 201 Created (resource created), 204 No Content (deleted), 400 Bad Request,
404 Not Found, 500 Internal Server Error

(ii) Use proper content types.
Content-Type: application/json
Support filtering, sorting, and pagination via query parameters.
/users?page=1&size=10&sort=name,asc

(iii) Version your API if needed.
/api/v1/users

4. Practical Examples

Good URI Design
/users (GET, POST)
/users/1 (GET, PUT, PATCH, DELETE)
/users/1/orders (GET all orders for user 1)

Bad URI Design
/getUser?id=1
/users/delete/1
/users_table

